      <h2>Channel-Native Adaptation</h2>
      <ShibuiContent id="distribution-strategy.channel-native-adaptation.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I do not cross-post -- I genuinely re-frame each piece of content for the channel it is going to. A Mastodon thread has different conventions than a newsletter digest, which is different from a GitHub Pages essay. Each channel gets content adapted to its discourse norms, not a copy-paste.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
		<p>
        The critical distinction in this distribution strategy is between cross-posting and <ShibuiTerm term="channel-native adaptation" definition="Genuinely re-framing content for each platform's discourse conventions, audience expectations, and technical affordances rather than copying identical text" />. Cross-posting takes a single piece of content and copies it to multiple platforms unchanged — a practice that violates the norms of every platform simultaneously. I implemented a genuine re-framing process for each channel's discourse conventions, audience expectations, and technical affordances.<Cite id={7} author="McLuhan, Marshall" title="Understanding Media: The Extensions of Man" source="McGraw-Hill" year={1964} />
      </p>
	</span>
      </ShibuiContent>
      <button class="shibui-bridge" type="button">This section goes deeper</button>

